{"title_page": "Little Rann of Kutch", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Rann of Kutch|Great Rann of Kutch}}\n{{copy edit|date=March 2020}}\n[[Image:Map GujDist Kuchchh.png|thumb|right|300px|Map of [[Gujarat]] showing the Little Rann of Kutch and Great Rann of Kutch]]\n[[File:Asiatic Wild ass.jpg|thumb|alt=|Asiatic Wild ass, popularly known as Ghudkhar in local language, in Little Rann of Kutch.]]\n'''Little desert of Kutch'''<ref>[http://www.indianexpress.com/news/needed-in-the-little-rann-of-kutch-a-marketing-strategy-worth-its-salt-to-help-the-agariyas/489339/0 Needed in the Little Rann of Kutch, a marketing strategy worth its salt to help the Agariyas] (2 page article online); by Adam Halliday; Jul 15, 2009; Indian Express Newspaper</ref><ref>[http://www.indianexpress.com/news/rti-revelation-govt-has-no-data-on-little-r/418466/ RTI revelation: govt has no data on Little Rann of Kutch] (2 page article online); by Kamran Sulaimani; Feb 03, 2009; Indian Express Newspaper</ref> is a [[salt marsh]] which is part of [[Rann of Kutch]] in [[Kutch district]], [[Gujarat]], India.\n[[File:Little Rann of Kutch West Part 1896.jpg|thumb|Little Rann of Kutch West Part 1896]][[File:Little Rann of Kutch East Part 1896.jpg|thumb|Little Rann of Kutch East Part 1896]]\n\n==Indian Wild Ass Sanctuary==\n[[File:IndianWildAss1.jpg|thumb|Indian wild ass herd in Little Rann of Kutch]]\n[[File:Flamingo LRK IMG 20161211 123643.jpg|thumb|Flock of Lesser Flamingo in Little Rann of Kutch]]\nLittle Rann of Kutch is a unique saline desert and is synonymous with the \u00a0[[Indian wild ass]](khur). To conserve this animal, an approximate area of about 4954 Sq.Kms was declared as the Indian Wild Ass Sanctuary in 1973.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forests.gujarat.gov.in/wild-ass-sanctuary.htm|title=Wild Ass Santuary|last=|first=|date=|website=forests.gujarat.gov.in|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> Though a bleak landscape, it is rich in biodiversity and existence of many rare and endangered local and migratory birds like Sarus crane, duck, Dalmatian pelican, flamingo, and land birds like the Sandgrouse, Francolin and the Indian bustard. It is also home to various mammals such as the [[Indian wolf]] (''Canis lupus pallipes''), [[White-footed fox|desert fox]] (''Vulpes vulpes pusilla'') and [[nilgai]] (''Boselaphus tragocamelus'').\n\n==Biosphere reserve - world heritage site==\nIn 2008, to project [[Kutch]] as an international nature destination, the [[Government of India|Government of Gujarat]] granted a much-awaited status of the [[Biosphere Reserve|Kutch Biosphere Reserve]], Recognized by [[UNESCO]] under its Man and Biosphere (MAB) programme. Biosphere reserves aim to promote sustainable development in the surrounding area which is reserved and managed for purposes of [[Conservation (ethic)|conservation]] and to provide special opportunities for study or [[research]]. Such Biosphere reserves are protected under the Wildlife Protection Act, Indian Forest Act and Forest Conservation Act. The Government not only provides funds for the conservation of landscape and biological diversity but also to preserve and promote cultural heritage, education and information exchange around the area. The vegetation around the reserve sanctuary is mainly [[Xerophyte|xerophytic]] as the groundwater lasts for a very short duration. The island covered within the sanctuary has around 253 flowering species. According to some estimates, about 70,000 to 75,000 birds nests in an area of about 250 acres.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/2105/|title=Wild Ass Santuary, Little Rann of Kutch|last=|first=|date=2015|website=UNESCO|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>[http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/Earth/Flora--Fauna/Kutch-gets-biosphere-reserve-status/articleshow/3261967.cms Kutch gets biosphere reserve status - The Greater and Little Rann of Kutch have finally got the much-awaited status of biosphere reserve.]</ref><ref>[http://www.indianexpress.com/news/kutchs-wild-ass-habitat-may-soon-get-herita/206928/ Kutch\u2019s wild ass habitat may soon get heritage label] (2 Page article online); by DP Bhattacharya; Jul 26, 2007; Indian Express Newspaper</ref>\n\n==Economy ==\n[[File:Salt Well Kutch Gujarat India 1891.jpg|thumb|Salt well in Kutch in 1891]]\n===Salt panning===\n[[File:Salt pane worker Chandra (16474712257).jpg|thumb|Salt pane worker|left]]\n[[Salt evaporation pond|Salt Panning]] is an important seasonal activity in the Rann of Kutch. During monsoon the underwater table of the Kutch is filled with Salty waters from the sea, as the water begins to recede in October, the century-old process of digging the wells for salt panning begins. '''Agariyas''', a community carrying out this Herculean task temporarily settles in this vast land and dig many wells to pump out the salty waters and fill-up the square-shaped fields, the natural climate conditions allow evaporation of the water and leave white crystals of salt. Harvesting seasons begin in the winter season to collect the raw salt from the fields, this process results in a collection of around 15 tons of salt with hard work of 15 days by the workers for a meagre sum of money. The salt panning workers face severe health-related issues due to working in the harsh conditions in the fields continuously for a period of 6-7 months.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mukherjee|first=Sugato|url=https://thediplomat.com/2016/10/the-salt-farmers-of-the-rann-of-kutch/|title=The Salt Farmers of the Rann of Kutch|date=3 October 2016|work=The Diplomat|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In a move to improve the financial conditions of the salt workers, Government of Gujarat came up with a scheme of financing the salt panning workers with [[Solar Panels]] to generate electricity, which would, in turn, be procured by the State Electricity Distribution Company. '''SEVA''' a [[Trade Union]] registered in 1972 by the poor, self-employed women workers in collaboration with [[Government of Gujarat]] is working towards the betterment of the traditional Salt Panning workers in the region by installing Solar Powered pumps in the desert, Which is aimed at eliminating [[Diesel engine]] powered [[Generators]] and Pumps resulting in reducing the cost of producing salt by one-third.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Pathak|first=Maulik|url=https://www.livemint.com/industry/energy/gujarat-govt-to-buy-solar-power-from-salt-pan-workers-1549458047228.html|title=Gujarat govt to buy solar power from salt pan workers|date=6 Feb 2019|work=LiveMint|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\n===Ginger Prawn Farming===\nThe Gulf of Kutch which has very vibrant [[Biodiversity]] is also considered as a highly productive ground for [[Fishery]]. Among many fishery resources, Prawn resources play a major role due to its high demand both in Domestic and International markets. And among many prawn resources, Ginger Prawn plays a significant role in the region as its highly seasonal during monsoon and indigenous of the species. The area which is dry during summers ranging from October-June, However, with the outset of monsoon, the fresh waters from [[Banas River|Banas]], [[Sarasvati River|Saraswati]] and [[Machchhu River|Machchu]] mix with the salty waters of Gulf of Kutch, This brings in an enormous influx of Ginger prawn juveniles into the Rann of Kutch, which is exploited in mass scale. Juveniles of Ginger Prawn which are also known as \u201cSurajbari\" prawns as fish processing units in [[Gujarat]] procure them from Surajbari area in the region. Apart from monsoon rains in the region, other chemical and biological parameters pertaining to the water in the region also plays an important role in the growth of these species from the stage of [[Larva|larvae]] to flourishing fishery around this region. The fishing in the region dates back to the early 16th century, During this period Muslim fishermen used to engage in fishing only for sustenance. The casting and retrieval of fishing nets were carried out manually by hand and the entire fishing operation was carried out barefoot. This way of fishing was known as \"Pagadia fishing\" which is in practice even today in the region.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gyanaranjan Dash, Swatipriyanka Sen,M Koya, KR Sreenath|first=Suresh Kumar Mojjada, and HM Bhint|date=2012|title=Ginger Prawn Fishery in Gulf of Kutch: A Seasonal Livelihood for the Traditional Fishermen|url=https://www.asianagrihistory.org/pdf/research/ginger-prawn-16-4.pdf|journal=Central Marine Fisheries Research Institute|volume=Asian Agri-History Vol. 16, No. 4|pages=1-9|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Damming Rann of Kutch===\n[[Government of Gujarat|Gujarat government]] is studying to dam the 1.26 km stretch of Hadakiya Creek of Rann of Kutch area so that impounded monsoon water can be used for recreational and fisheries purposes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eye on 2019 polls? Tycoon discusses with Modi, Amit Shah Asia's biggest Rann Sarovar sweet water lake in Gujarat|url=https://www.counterview.net/2018/05/eye-on-2019-polls-tycoon-discusses-with.html|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Wildlife sanctuaries and reserves of Kutch==\nFrom the city of [[Bhuj]] various [[ecology|ecologically]] rich and [[wildlife conservation]] areas of the Kutch/[[Kachchh district]] can be visited such as the [[Indian Wild Ass Sanctuary]], the [[Kutch Desert Wildlife Sanctuary]], the [[Narayan Sarovar Sanctuary]], the [[Kutch Bustard Sanctuary]], the [[Banni Grasslands Reserve]] and the [[Chari-Dhand Wetland Conservation Reserve]].\n[[File:Yellow Throated Sparrow in LRK.jpg|thumb|Yellow Throated Sparrow in LRK]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Arid Forest Research Institute]] (AFRI)\n* [[Great Rann of Kutch]]\n* [[Indian wild ass]]\n* [[Kutch District]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* {{WWF ecoregion|name=Rann of Kutch seasonal salt marsh |id=im0901}} This text was originally published in the book Terrestrial ecoregions of the Indo-Pacific: a conservation assessment from Island Press. Also see: {{NatGeo ecoregion|id=im0901|name=Rann of Kutch seasonal salt marsh}}\n\n==External links==\n{{external links|date=December 2019}}\n*[http://www.hindu.com/2009/04/23/stories/2009042350291500.htm The salt of the earth - The Little Rann of Kutch contributes about 60 percent of the salt manufactured in the country. But Gujarat\u2019s politicians have done little for the Agariya community that produces it.]; by Manas Dasgupta; Apr 23, 2009; The Hindu, Online edition of India's National Newspaper\n*[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-04-11/ahmedabad/28050560_1_nal-sarovar-first-census-wild-asses Wild asses population rises by 4%]; TNN; 11 April 2009; Times of India\n*[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-04-09/ahmedabad/28034743_1_equine-flu-forest-officials-virus Wild Ass vulnerable to flu]; by TNN; 9 April 2009; Times of India\n*[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-03-31/rajkot/28028104_1_census-teams-wild-boar-sanctuary Wild ass census to kick off from April 5]; TNN; 31 March 2009; Times of India\n*[http://www.commodityonline.com/news/Bleak-future-for-traditional-salt-15393-3-1.html Bleak future for traditional salt]; by Anosh Malekar; February 21, 2009; Courtesy : Infochange News & Features; ComodittyOnline\n*[http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/Earth/Flora--Fauna/Kutch-gets-biosphere-reserve-status/articleshow/3261967.cms Kutch gets biosphere reserve status - The Greater and Little Rann of Kutch have finally got the much-awaited status of biosphere reserve.]; Himanshu Kaushik, TNN; 22 Jul 2008; Economic Times; Times of India\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20121002221224/http://www.expressindia.com/latest-news/agariyas-wait-for-land-rights-continues-even-after-intervention-by-cmo/286054/ Agariyas\u2019 wait for land rights continues even after intervention by CMO]; Express news service; Mar 19, 2008; Indian Express Newspaper\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20121002221047/http://www.expressindia.com/latest-news/kutch-branch-canal-through-sanctuary-not-to-hamper-movement-of-wild-ass/273609/ Kutch Branch Canal through sanctuary not to hamper the movement of wild ass]; BASHIR PATHAN; Feb 16, 2008; Indian Express Newspaper\n*[http://www.indianexpress.com/news/kutchs-wild-ass-habitat-may-soon-get-herita/206928/ Kutch\u2019s wild ass habitat may soon get heritage label] (2 Page article online); by DP Bhattacharya; Jul 26, 2007; Indian Express Newspaper\n*[http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2007/04/09/stories/2007040902591500.htm Salt-makers in Gujarat face eviction]; by Virendra Pandit; Apr 09, 2007; Business Line, Business Daily from THE HINDU group of publications\n*[http://www.rediff.com/news/2007/feb/15rann.htm Wild ass robs agarias' livelihood]; February 15, 2007; Rediff India Abroad\n*[http://www.hindu.com/mp/2006/03/04/stories/2006030400320200.htm Indian Wild Ass Sanctuary]; SANCTUARY SPOTLIGHT; Mar 04, 2006; The Hindu, Online edition of India's National Newspaper. Also posted at [http://www.hindu.com/mp/2006/02/27/stories/2006022700320300.htm]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130509024619/http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=67090 Japanese duo does donkey work in Rann - \u2018\u2018The female donkeys are left by the maldhari\u2019s on the island of Plaswa village in the Rann of Kutch for about three months during the monsoon. Here, the Wild Ass, a protected species, breed with the female donkeys leading to the birth of hybrid donkeys which are taller than their mothers and wilder than their fathers,\u2019\u2019 says Dr R Kimura who has been a visiting researcher at the Equine Museum of Japan for the past two decades.]; by Rupam Jain; November 3, 2003; Indian Express Newspaper. Also see [http://www.indianexpress.com/oldStory/34794/]\n*[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2003-11-28/ahmedabad/27185200_1_census-staff-lone-sanctuary-officials-gear Officials gear up for wild ass census]; by TNN;  28 November 2003; Times of India\n*[http://www.indianexpress.com/res/web/pIe/ie/daily/19990308/ige08141.html Wild ass being robbed of its run of the Little Rann]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}; by ANAND SUNDAS; March 8, 1999; Indian Express Newspaper\n*[http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?205158 Salt In The Wounds - Gandhi's historic Dandi march has bypassed them. Gujarat's salt workers are caught up in a maze of abysmal living conditions, ignorance and neglect.] By SAIRA MENEZES; Mar 02, 1998;Outlook India Magazine\n\n{{GeoSouthAsia}}\n\n{{coord|23.3000|N|71.2000|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Little Rann Of Kutch}}\n[[Category:Indomalaya ecozone]]\n[[Category:Flooded grasslands and savannas]]\n[[Category:Grasslands of India]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Marshes of India]]\n[[Category:Salt marshes]]\n[[Category:Geography of Kutch district]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Rann of Kutch|Great Rann of Kutch}}\n{{copy edit|date=March 2020}}\n[[Image:Map GujDist Kuchchh.png|thumb|right|300px|Map of [[Gujarat]] showing the Little Rann of Kutch and Great Rann of Kutch]]\n[[File:Asiatic Wild ass.jpg|thumb|alt=|Asiatic Wild ass, popularly known as Ghudkhar in local language, in Little Rann of Kutch.]]\n'''Little desert of Kutch'''<ref>[http://www.indianexpress.com/news/needed-in-the-little-rann-of-kutch-a-marketing-strategy-worth-its-salt-to-help-the-agariyas/489339/0 Needed in the Little Rann of Kutch, a marketing strategy worth its salt to help the Agariyas] (2 page article online); by Adam Halliday; Jul 15, 2009; Indian Express Newspaper</ref><ref>[http://www.indianexpress.com/news/rti-revelation-govt-has-no-data-on-little-r/418466/ RTI revelation: govt has no data on Little Rann of Kutch] (2 page article online); by Kamran Sulaimani; Feb 03, 2009; Indian Express Newspaper</ref> is a [[salt marsh]] which is part of [[Rann of Kutch]] in [[Kutch district]], [[Gujarat]], India.\n[[File:Little Rann of Kutch West Part 1896.jpg|thumb|Little Rann of Kutch West Part 1896]][[File:Little Rann of Kutch East Part 1896.jpg|thumb|Little Rann of Kutch East Part 1896]]\n\n==Indian Wild Ass Sanctuary==\n[[File:IndianWildAss1.jpg|thumb|Indian wild ass herd in Little Rann of Kutch]]\n[[File:Flamingo LRK IMG 20161211 123643.jpg|thumb|Flock of Lesser Flamingo in Little Rann of Kutch]]\nLittle Rann of Kutch is a unique saline desert and is synonymous with the \u00a0[[Indian wild ass]](khur). To conserve this animal, an approximate area of about 4954 Sq.Kms was declared as the Indian Wild Ass Sanctuary in 1973.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forests.gujarat.gov.in/wild-ass-sanctuary.htm|title=Wild Ass Santuary|last=|first=|date=|website=forests.gujarat.gov.in|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> Though a bleak landscape, it is rich in biodiversity and existence of many rare and endangered local and migratory birds like Sarus crane, duck, Dalmatian pelican, flamingo, and land birds like the Sandgrous, Francolin and the Indian bustard. It is also home to various mammals such as the [[Indian wolf]] (''Canis lupus pallipes''), [[White-footed fox|desert fox]] (''Vulpes vulpes pusilla'') and [[nilgai]] (''Boselaphus tragocamelus'').\n\n==Biosphere reserve - world heritage site==\nIn 2008, to project [[Kutch]] as an international nature destination, the [[Government of India|Government of Gujarat]] granted a much-awaited status of the [[Biosphere Reserve|Kutch Biosphere Reserve]], Recognized by [[UNESCO]] under its Man and Biosphere (MAB) programme. Biosphere reserves aim to promote sustainable development in the surrounding area which is reserved and managed for purposes of [[Conservation (ethic)|conservation]] and to provide special opportunities for study or [[research]]. Such Biosphere reserves are protected under the Wildlife Protection Act, Indian Forest Act and Forest Conservation Act. The Government not only provides funds for the conservation of landscape and biological diversity but also to preserve and promote cultural heritage, education and information exchange around the area. The vegetation around the reserve sanctuary is mainly [[Xerophyte|xerophytic]] as the groundwater lasts for a very short duration. The island covered within the sanctuary has around 253 flowering species. According to some estimates, about 70,000 to 75,000 birds nests in an area of about 250 acres.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/2105/|title=Wild Ass Santuary, Little Rann of Kutch|last=|first=|date=2015|website=UNESCO|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>[http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/Earth/Flora--Fauna/Kutch-gets-biosphere-reserve-status/articleshow/3261967.cms Kutch gets biosphere reserve status - The Greater and Little Rann of Kutch have finally got the much-awaited status of biosphere reserve.]</ref><ref>[http://www.indianexpress.com/news/kutchs-wild-ass-habitat-may-soon-get-herita/206928/ Kutch\u2019s wild ass habitat may soon get heritage label] (2 Page article online); by DP Bhattacharya; Jul 26, 2007; Indian Express Newspaper</ref>\n\n==Economy ==\n[[File:Salt Well Kutch Gujarat India 1891.jpg|thumb|Salt well in Kutch in 1891]]\n===Salt panning===\n[[File:Salt pane worker Chandra (16474712257).jpg|thumb|Salt pane worker|left]]\n[[Salt evaporation pond|Salt Panning]] is an important seasonal activity in the Rann of Kutch. During monsoon the underwater table of the Kutch is filled with Salty waters from the sea, as the water begins to recede in October, the century-old process of digging the wells for salt panning begins. '''Agariyas''', a community carrying out this Herculean task temporarily settles in this vast land and dig many wells to pump out the salty waters and fill-up the square-shaped fields, the natural climate conditions allow evaporation of the water and leave white crystals of salt. Harvesting seasons begin in the winter season to collect the raw salt from the fields, this process results in a collection of around 15 tons of salt with hard work of 15 days by the workers for a meagre sum of money. The salt panning workers face severe health-related issues due to working in the harsh conditions in the fields continuously for a period of 6-7 months.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mukherjee|first=Sugato|url=https://thediplomat.com/2016/10/the-salt-farmers-of-the-rann-of-kutch/|title=The Salt Farmers of the Rann of Kutch|date=3 October 2016|work=The Diplomat|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In a move to improve the financial conditions of the salt workers, Government of Gujarat came up with a scheme of financing the salt panning workers with [[Solar Panels]] to generate electricity, which would, in turn, be procured by the State Electricity Distribution Company. '''SEVA''' a [[Trade Union]] registered in 1972 by the poor, self-employed women workers in collaboration with [[Government of Gujarat]] is working towards the betterment of the traditional Salt Panning workers in the region by installing Solar Powered pumps in the desert, Which is aimed at eliminating [[Diesel engine]] powered [[Generators]] and Pumps resulting in reducing the cost of producing salt by one-third.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Pathak|first=Maulik|url=https://www.livemint.com/industry/energy/gujarat-govt-to-buy-solar-power-from-salt-pan-workers-1549458047228.html|title=Gujarat govt to buy solar power from salt pan workers|date=6 Feb 2019|work=LiveMint|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\n===Ginger Prawn Farming===\nThe Gulf of Kutch which has very vibrant [[Biodiversity]] is also considered as a highly productive ground for [[Fishery]]. Among many fishery resources, Prawn resources play a major role due to its high demand both in Domestic and International markets. And among many prawn resources, Ginger Prawn plays a significant role in the region as its highly seasonal during monsoon and indigenous of the species. The area which is dry during summers ranging from October-June, However, with the outset of monsoon, the fresh waters from [[Banas River|Banas]], [[Sarasvati River|Saraswati]] and [[Machchhu River|Machchu]] mix with the salty waters of Gulf of Kutch, This brings in an enormous influx of Ginger prawn juveniles into the Rann of Kutch, which is exploited in mass scale. Juveniles of Ginger Prawn which are also known as \u201cSurajbari\" prawns as fish processing units in [[Gujarat]] procure them from Surajbari area in the region. Apart from monsoon rains in the region, other chemical and biological parameters pertaining to the water in the region also plays an important role in the growth of these species from the stage of [[Larva|larvae]] to flourishing fishery around this region. The fishing in the region dates back to the early 16th century, During this period Muslim fishermen used to engage in fishing only for sustenance. The casting and retrieval of fishing nets were carried out manually by hand and the entire fishing operation was carried out barefoot. This way of fishing was known as \"Pagadia fishing\" which is in practice even today in the region.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gyanaranjan Dash, Swatipriyanka Sen,M Koya, KR Sreenath|first=Suresh Kumar Mojjada, and HM Bhint|date=2012|title=Ginger Prawn Fishery in Gulf of Kutch: A Seasonal Livelihood for the Traditional Fishermen|url=https://www.asianagrihistory.org/pdf/research/ginger-prawn-16-4.pdf|journal=Central Marine Fisheries Research Institute|volume=Asian Agri-History Vol. 16, No. 4|pages=1-9|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Damming Rann of Kutch===\n[[Government of Gujarat|Gujarat government]] is studying to dam the 1.26 km stretch of Hadakiya Creek of Rann of Kutch area so that impounded monsoon water can be used for recreational and fisheries purposes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eye on 2019 polls? Tycoon discusses with Modi, Amit Shah Asia's biggest Rann Sarovar sweet water lake in Gujarat|url=https://www.counterview.net/2018/05/eye-on-2019-polls-tycoon-discusses-with.html|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Wildlife sanctuaries and reserves of Kutch==\nFrom the city of [[Bhuj]] various [[ecology|ecologically]] rich and [[wildlife conservation]] areas of the Kutch/[[Kachchh district]] can be visited such as the [[Indian Wild Ass Sanctuary]], the [[Kutch Desert Wildlife Sanctuary]], the [[Narayan Sarovar Sanctuary]], the [[Kutch Bustard Sanctuary]], the [[Banni Grasslands Reserve]] and the [[Chari-Dhand Wetland Conservation Reserve]].\n[[File:Yellow Throated Sparrow in LRK.jpg|thumb|Yellow Throated Sparrow in LRK]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Arid Forest Research Institute]] (AFRI)\n* [[Great Rann of Kutch]]\n* [[Indian wild ass]]\n* [[Kutch District]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* {{WWF ecoregion|name=Rann of Kutch seasonal salt marsh |id=im0901}} This text was originally published in the book Terrestrial ecoregions of the Indo-Pacific: a conservation assessment from Island Press. Also see: {{NatGeo ecoregion|id=im0901|name=Rann of Kutch seasonal salt marsh}}\n\n==External links==\n{{external links|date=December 2019}}\n*[http://www.hindu.com/2009/04/23/stories/2009042350291500.htm The salt of the earth - The Little Rann of Kutch contributes about 60 percent of the salt manufactured in the country. But Gujarat\u2019s politicians have done little for the Agariya community that produces it.]; by Manas Dasgupta; Apr 23, 2009; The Hindu, Online edition of India's National Newspaper\n*[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-04-11/ahmedabad/28050560_1_nal-sarovar-first-census-wild-asses Wild asses population rises by 4%]; TNN; 11 April 2009; Times of India\n*[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-04-09/ahmedabad/28034743_1_equine-flu-forest-officials-virus Wild Ass vulnerable to flu]; by TNN; 9 April 2009; Times of India\n*[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-03-31/rajkot/28028104_1_census-teams-wild-boar-sanctuary Wild a